# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cleveland-guardians
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1869 throughout the world.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] At its December 1868 meeting the NABBP permitted professional clubs for the first time.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] There had been no professional clubs outside the Association, and no brand new professional clubs were established for 1869.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] Rather, the entire first-year effect of the change was that twelve existing members declared professional status.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] All of them had fielded at least regionally strong teams in 1868 and most if not all had compensated at least some of their players.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] The Cincinnati Red Stockings were first to sign an all-salary team, ten men for eight months.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] From the west, the strongest team in Cleveland also joined the pro field.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] From the eastern corridor there were ten including all of the one-time champions and claimants.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] Otherwise the record of professional matches (see table) is remarkable for its balance, relative to the records of the stronger teams during the amateur era and to most of the following pro seasons.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] The Irvingtons did not travel, or win; after July they played only two matches with the Mutuals (four in all).
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] Forest City of Cleveland did not travel far, only to Cincinnati and upstate New York.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] Those two did not face each other or any of the three teams standing just above them.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] That imbalance, typical of the time, contributed to the losing records of all five.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] Weaker teams were weaker gate attractions with less incentive and almost always less ability to travel.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] The Irvingtons disbanded and the Keystones returned to amateur ranks, but all the others remained in the professional field for 1870.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] Indeed, all but Cincinnati remained in operation at least to 1872.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] The amateur ranks during 1869 probably included some clubs who compensated their players by traditional methods such as division of the gate receipts (as Spalding said of Rockford by the end of the decade).
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] Four of the amateurs would "go pro" in 1870, including the Forest City of Rockford, Illinois, with some success.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] The professional field was relatively strong in 1869 and its weaker teams did not play many games.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] The Forest Citys did not beat any pro teams, but they played only four matches with Cincinnati, losing three by twenty runs and one by merely 14–15 on July 24.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] (They traveled no further than Detroit and Ohio while eastern pros also traveled no further than Ohio, home of their westernmost rivals.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] The Stars of Brooklyn, led by pitcher Candy Cummings, won 2 of 7 matches with pro teams, beating the Mutuals 26–12 on June 19 and the visiting Olympics of Washington 49–11 on July 19.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] They lost five to the Mutuals and Atlantics by only 28 runs, total margin.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] Harvard college won 1 of 6 against pros, beating the powerful Athletics of Philadelphia 35–21 on July 9; the next day they lost a close one to the much weaker Keystones.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] Against amateurs Star won fourteen with one defeat; Harvard won thirteen with one draw.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] Next season they would win six each against the slightly larger pro field.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] Lowell of Boston, listed among the major teams by Bill Ryczek, played three fairly close game against the pros, losing 21–26 to the Mutuals, 9–29 to undefeated Red Stockings, and 33–38 to the Eckfords.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] Pastime of Baltimore won 2 of 9 against pro teams, including 1 of 4 local matches Maryland and one with the Troy Haymakers.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] The Olympics, Mutuals, Athletics, and Keystones beat them four teams by only 32 runs, total margin.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] Resolute of Elizabeth, New Jersey beat Irvington 16–15 and lost twice to the Eckfords.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] These six amateur teams barely faced each other on the field: Lowell lost six to its local rival Harvard and one to Star (July 5, the Fourth being a Sunday that year).
[src:cleveland-guardians/1869-in-baseball] Harvard toured for ten days but played only the professional Eckfords in New York City.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The **Great Chicago Fire** was a conflagration that burned in Chicago, Illinois, United States, during October 8–10, 1871.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The fire killed approximately 300 people, destroyed 17,000 structures across roughly 3.3 square miles (9 km2), and left more than 100,000 residents homeless.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The fire began in a neighborhood southwest of the city center.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] A long period of hot, dry, windy conditions, and the wooden construction prevalent in the city, led to the conflagration spreading quickly.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The fire leapt the south branch of the Chicago River and destroyed much of central Chicago and then crossed the main stem of the river, consuming the Near North Side.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Help flowed to the city from near and far after the fire.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The city government improved building codes to stop the rapid spread of future fires and rebuilt rapidly to those higher standards.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] A donation from the United Kingdom spurred the establishment of the Chicago Public Library.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] According to Nancy Connolly, great-great-granddaughter of Catherine O'Leary, the fire is said to have started at about 8:30 p.m. on October 8, in or around a small barn belonging to the O'Leary family that bordered the alley behind 137 W.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] DeKoven Street when Daniel "Peg-Leg" Sullivan accidentally knocked over a lantern while looking for beer for a party.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The shed next to the barn was the first building to be consumed by the fire.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] City officials never determined the cause of the blaze, but the rapid spread of the fire due to a long drought in that year's summer, strong winds from the southwest, and the rapid destruction of the water pumping system explain the extensive damage of the mainly wooden city structures.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] There has been much speculation over the years on the single start to the fire.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The most historically popular tale blames Mrs.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] O'Leary's cow, which allegedly knocked over a lantern; others state that a group of men were gambling inside the barn and knocked over a lantern.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Still other speculation suggests that the blaze was related to other fires in the Midwest that day.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] In 1997, the Chicago City Council formally exonerated O'Leary of any responsibility for the fire, following research by historian Richard Bales.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The fire's spread was aided by the city's use of wood as the predominant building material in a style called balloon frame.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] More than two-thirds of the structures in Chicago at the time of the fire were made entirely of wood, with most of the houses and buildings being topped with highly combustible tar or shingle roofs.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] All of the city's sidewalks and many roads were also made of wood.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Compounding this problem, Chicago received only 1 inch (25 mm) of rain from July 4 to October 9, causing severe drought conditions before the fire, while strong southwest winds helped to carry flying embers toward the heart of the city.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] In 1871, the Chicago Fire Department had 185 firefighters with just 17 horse-drawn steam pumpers to protect the entire city.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The initial response by the fire department was timely, but due to an error by the watchman, Mathias Schaffer, the firefighters were initially sent to the wrong place, allowing the fire to grow unchecked.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] An alarm sent from the area near the fire also failed to register at the courthouse where the fire watchmen were, while the firefighters were tired from having fought numerous small fires and one large fire in the week before.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] These factors combined to turn a small barn fire into a conflagration.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] When firefighters finally arrived at DeKoven Street, the fire had grown and spread to neighboring buildings and was progressing toward the central business district.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Firefighters had hoped that the South Branch of the Chicago River and an area that had previously thoroughly burned would act as a natural firebreak.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] All along the river, however, were lumber yards, warehouses, and coal yards, as well as barges, and numerous bridges across the river.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] As the fire grew, the southwest wind intensified and the temperature rose, causing structures to catch fire from the heat and from burning debris blown by the wind.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Around midnight, flaming debris blew across the river and landed on roofs and the South Side Gas Works.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] With the fire across the river and moving rapidly toward the heart of the city, panic set in.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Mason sent messages to nearby towns asking for help.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] When the courthouse caught fire, he ordered the building to be evacuated and the prisoners jailed in the basement to be released.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] At 2:30 a.m. on the 9th, the cupola of the courthouse collapsed, sending the great bell crashing down.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Some witnesses reported hearing the sound from a mile (1.6 km) away.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] As more buildings succumbed to the flames, a major contributing factor to the fire's spread was a meteorological phenomenon known as a fire whirl.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] As hot air rises, it comes into contact with cooler air and begins to spin, creating a tornado-like effect.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] These fire whirls are likely what drove flaming debris so high and so far.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Such debris was blown across the main branch of the Chicago River to a railroad car carrying kerosene.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The fire had jumped the river a second time and was now raging across the city's north side.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Despite the fire spreading and growing rapidly, the city's firefighters continued to battle the blaze.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] A short time after the fire jumped the river, a burning piece of timber lodged on the roof of the city's waterworks.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Within minutes, the interior of the building was engulfed in flames and the building was destroyed.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] With it, the city's water mains went dry and the city was helpless.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Contemporary Chicago Tribune reporting confirmed that the waterworks roof caught fire at an early hour, forcing firefighters to retreat before the building was lost.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The fire burned unchecked from building to building, block to block.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] One eyewitness account, reprinted from a Western paper, described a family trapped on the fourth floor of a building at the corner of Randolph and Market Streets, the father throwing his wife and children to safety below before collapsing beside his wife as the flames closed in.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Late in the evening of October 9, it started to rain, but the fire had already started to burn itself out.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The fire had spread to the sparsely populated areas of the north side, having thoroughly consumed the densely populated areas.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Once the fire had ended, the smoldering remains were still too hot for a survey of the damage to be completed for many days.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Eventually, the city determined that the fire destroyed an area about 4 miles (6 km) long and averaging 3⁄4 mile (1 km) wide, encompassing an area of more than 2,000 acres (809 ha).
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Destroyed were more than 73 miles (117 km) of roads, 120 miles (190 km) of sidewalk, 2,000 lampposts, 17,500 buildings, and $222 million in property, which was about a third of the city's valuation in 1871.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Sheridan's command structure consisted of a mix of regular troops, militia units, police, and a specially organized civilian group "First Regiment of Chicago Volunteers".
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Former Lieutenant-Governor William Bross, and part owner of the *Tribune*, later recollected his response to the arrival of Gen.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Sheridan and his soldiers: "Never did deeper emotions of joy overcome me.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Thank God, those most dear to me and the city as well are safe." For two weeks, Sheridan's men patrolled the streets, guarded the relief warehouses, and enforced other regulations.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] On October 24 the troops were relieved of their duties and the volunteers were mustered out of service.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Of the approximately 324,000 inhabitants of Chicago in 1871, 90,000 Chicago residents (about 28% of the population) were left homeless.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] 120 bodies were recovered, but the death toll may have been as high as 300.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The county coroner speculated that an accurate count was impossible, as some victims may have drowned or had been incinerated, leaving no remains.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] In the days and weeks following the fire, monetary donations flowed into Chicago from around the country and abroad, along with donations of food, clothing, and other goods.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] These donations came from individuals, corporations, and cities.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] New York City gave $450,000 (equivalent to $12.1 million today) along with clothing and provisions, St.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Louis gave $300,000 (equivalent to $8.06 million today), and the Common Council of London gave 1,000 guineas, as well as £7,000 from private donations.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] 40,000) a town meeting raised £518 on the spot.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Cincinnati, Cleveland, and Buffalo, all commercial rivals, donated hundreds and thousands of dollars.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Milwaukee, along with other nearby cities, helped by sending fire-fighting equipment.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Food, clothing and books were brought by train from all over the continent.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Mayor Mason placed the Chicago Relief and Aid Society in charge of the city's relief efforts.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Operating from the First Congregational Church, city officials and aldermen began taking steps to preserve order in Chicago.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Price gouging was a key concern, and in one ordinance, the city set the price of bread at 8¢ for a 12-ounce (340 g) loaf.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Public buildings were opened as places of refuge, and saloons closed at 9 in the evening for the week following the fire.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Many people who were left homeless after the incident were never able to get their normal lives back since all their personal papers and belongings burned in the conflagration.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Tribune reporting also documented deliberate arson during the chaos: one man set fire to the Jesuit Church on the West Side, while a woman was arrested for firing a building on Burnside Street; the man was caught by neighbors, stoned, and beaten to death on the spot.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Burgess of London proposed an "English Book Donation", to spur a free library in Chicago, in their sympathy with Chicago over the damages suffered.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Libraries in Chicago had been private with membership fees.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] In April 1872, the City Council passed the ordinance to establish the free Chicago Public Library, starting with the donation from the United Kingdom of more than 8,000 volumes.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The fire also led to questions about development in the United States.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Due to Chicago's rapid expansion at that time, the fire led to Americans reflecting on industrialization.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Based on a religious point of view, some said that Americans should return to a more old-fashioned way of life, and that the fire was caused by people ignoring traditional morality.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] On the other hand, others believed that a lesson to be learned from the fire was that cities needed to improve their building techniques.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Olmsted also believed that with brick walls, and disciplined firemen and police, the deaths and damage caused would have been much less.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Almost immediately, the city began to rewrite its fire standards, spurred by the efforts of leading insurance executives, and fire-prevention reformers such as Arthur C.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Chicago soon developed one of the country's leading fire-fighting forces.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Business owners and land speculators such as Gurdon Saltonstall Hubbard quickly set about rebuilding the city.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The first load of lumber for rebuilding was delivered the day the last burning building was extinguished.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] By the World's Columbian Exposition 22 years later, Chicago hosted more than 21 million visitors.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The Palmer House hotel burned to the ground in the fire 13 days after its grand opening.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Its developer, Potter Palmer, secured a loan and rebuilt the hotel to higher standards, across the street from the original, proclaiming it to be "The World's First Fireproof Building".
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] In 1956, the remaining structures on the original O'Leary property at 558 W.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] DeKoven Street were torn down for construction of the Chicago Fire Academy, a training facility for Chicago firefighters, known as the Quinn Fire Academy or Chicago Fire Department Training Facility.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] A bronze sculpture of stylized flames, entitled *Pillar of Fire* by Egon Weiner, was erected on the point of origin in 1961.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Michael's Church and the Pumping Station were both gutted in the fire, but their exteriors survived, and the buildings were rebuilt using the surviving walls.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Additionally, though the inhabitable portions of the building were destroyed, the bell tower of St.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] James Cathedral survived the fire and was incorporated into the rebuilt church.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The stones near the top of the tower are still blackened from the soot and smoke.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Almost from the moment the fire broke out, various theories about its cause began to circulate.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The most popular and enduring legend maintains that the fire began in the O'Leary barn as Mrs.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The cow kicked over a lantern (or an oil lamp in some versions), setting fire to the barn.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The O'Leary family denied this, stating that they were in bed before the fire started, but stories of the cow began to spread across the city.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Catherine O'Leary seemed the perfect scapegoat: she was a poor, Irish Catholic immigrant.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] During the latter half of the 19th century, anti-Irish sentiment was strong in Chicago and throughout the United States.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] This was intensified as a result of the growing political power of the city's Irish population.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Furthermore, the United States had been distrustful of Catholics (or papists, as they were often called) since its beginning, carrying over attitudes in England in the 17th century; as an Irish Catholic, Mrs.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] O'Leary was a target of both anti-Catholic and anti-Irish sentiment.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] This story was circulating in Chicago even before the flames had died out, and it was noted in the *Chicago Tribune'*s first post-fire issue.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] In 1893 the reporter Michael Ahern retracted the "cow-and-lantern" story, admitting it was fabricated, but even his confession was unable to put the legend to rest.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Although the O'Learys were never officially charged with starting the fire, the story became so engrained in local lore that Chicago's city council officially exonerated them—and the cow—in 1997.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Amateur historian Richard Bales has suggested the fire started when Daniel "Pegleg" Sullivan, who first reported the fire, ignited hay in the barn while trying to steal milk.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Bales's account does not have consensus.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The Chicago Public Library staff criticized his account in their web page on the fire.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Despite this, the Chicago city council was convinced of Bales's argument and stated that the actions of Sullivan on that day should be scrutinized after the O'Leary family was exonerated in 1997.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Anthony DeBartolo reported evidence in two articles of the *Chicago Tribune* (October 8, 1997, and March 3, 1998, reprinted in *Hyde Park Media*) suggesting that Louis M.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Cohn may have started the fire during a craps game.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Following his death in 1942, Cohn bequeathed $35,000 which was assigned by his executors to the Medill School of Journalism at Northwestern University.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The bequest was given to the school on September 28, 1944, and the dedication contained a claim by Cohn to have been present at the start of the fire.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] According to Cohn, on the night of the fire, he was gambling in the O'Learys' barn with one of their sons and some other neighborhood boys.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] O'Leary came out to the barn to chase the gamblers away at around 9:00, they knocked over a lantern in their flight, although Cohn states that he paused long enough to scoop up the money.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The argument is not universally accepted.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] An alternative theory, first suggested in 1882 by Ignatius L.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Donnelly in *Ragnarok: The Age of Fire and Gravel*, is that the fire was caused by a meteor shower.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] This was described as a "fringe theory" concerning Biela's Comet.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] At a 2004 conference of the Aerospace Corporation and the American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics, engineer and physicist Robert Wood suggested that the fire began when a fragment of Biela's Comet impacted the Midwest.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Biela's Comet had broken apart in 1845 and had not been observed since.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Wood argued that four large fires took place, all on the same day, all on the shores of Lake Michigan (see related events), suggesting a common root cause.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Eyewitnesses reported sighting spontaneous ignitions, lack of smoke, "balls of fire" falling from the sky, and blue flames.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] According to Wood, these accounts suggest that the fires were caused by the methane that is commonly found in comets.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Meteorites are not known to start or spread fires and are cool to the touch after reaching the ground, so this theory has not found favor in the scientific community.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Methane-air mixtures become flammable only when the methane concentration exceeds 5%, at which point the mixtures also become explosive, a situation unlikely to occur from meteorites.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Methane gas is lighter than air and thus does not accumulate near the ground; any localized pockets of methane in the open air rapidly dissipate.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Moreover, if a fragment of an icy comet were to strike the Earth, the most likely outcome, due to the low tensile strength of such bodies, would be for it to disintegrate in the upper atmosphere, leading to a meteor air burst like the Tunguska event.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The specific choice of Biela's Comet does not match with the dates in question, as the 6-year period of the comet's orbit did not intersect that of the Earth until 1872, one full year after the fire, when a large meteor shower was observed.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] A common cause for the fires in the Midwest in late 1871 is that the area had had a dry summer, so that winds from the front that moved in that evening were capable of generating rapidly expanding blazes from available ignition sources, which were plentiful in the region.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] On that hot, dry, and windy autumn day, three other major fires occurred along the shores of Lake Michigan at the same time as the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Some 250 miles (400 km) to the north, the Peshtigo Fire consumed the town of Peshtigo, Wisconsin, along with a dozen other villages.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] It killed 1,200 to 2,500 people and charred approximately 1.5 million acres (6,100 km2).
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The Peshtigo Fire remains the deadliest in American history but the remoteness of the region meant it was little noticed at the time, because one of the first things that burned were the telegraph lines to Green Bay.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Across the lake to the east, the town of Holland, Michigan, and other nearby areas burned to the ground.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Some 100 miles (160 km) to the north of Holland, the lumbering community of Manistee also went up in flames in what became known as the Great Michigan Fire.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Farther east, along the shore of Lake Huron, the Port Huron Fire swept through Port Huron, Michigan and much of Michigan's "Thumb".
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] On October 9, 1871, a fire swept through the city of Urbana, Illinois, 140 miles (230 km) south of Chicago, destroying portions of its downtown area.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] Windsor, Ontario, likewise burned on October 12.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] The town of Singapore, Michigan, provided a large portion of the lumber to rebuild Chicago.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1871-great-chicago-fire] As a result, Singapore was so heavily deforested that the land deteriorated into barren sand dunes that buried the town, which had to be abandoned.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The **1894 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1894.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 30, with the Baltimore Orioles as the pennant winner of the National League and the New York Giants as runner-up.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the first Temple Cup on October 4 and ended with Game 4 on October 8.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The Giants swept the Orioles, capturing their first Temple Cup.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The 1894 season saw the return of a postseason championship series, the Temple Cup, following the end of the World's Championship Series with the demise of the American Association in 1891 and the one-off, split-season 1892 World's Championship Series.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The 1894 schedule consisted of 132 games for the twelve teams of the National League.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other eleven teams in the league.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1894-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place in the previous season and would be used until 1898.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring eight teams.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, also featuring eight teams.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The Temple Cup took place between October 4 and October 8.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Makeshift stands built for remainder of the season, from August 18.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1894-major-league-baseball-season] 16 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the start of the season, the Cincinnati Reds' home as League Park saw major changes.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1894-major-league-baseball-season] A new grandstand in what was left field was built, as well as an ampitheater.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The baseball diamond was shifted from the southeast corner of the lot to the southwest corner, with the original seating retained as right field seating.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1896-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1896 throughout the world.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1896-major-league-baseball-season] The **1896 major league baseball season** began on April 16, 1896.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1896-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 26, with the Baltimore Orioles as the pennant winner of the National League and the Cleveland Spiders as runner-up.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1896-major-league-baseball-season] In a rematch of the previous season, the postseason began with Game 1 of the third Temple Cup on October 2 and ended with Game 4 on October 8.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1896-major-league-baseball-season] The Orioles swept the Spiders, capturing their first Temple Cup.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1896-major-league-baseball-season] The 1896 Temple Cup was the only one of four Temple Cups which saw the NL pennant winner win the championship series.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1896-major-league-baseball-season] The 1896 schedule consisted of 132 games for the twelve teams of the National League.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1896-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since 1893 and would be used until 1898.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1896-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 16 featuring all twelve teams.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1896-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 26, featuring ten teams.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1896-major-league-baseball-season] The Temple Cup took place between October 2 and October 8.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1896-major-league-baseball-season] The 1896 season featured an extremely rare tripleheader—the second of three in National League and major-league history, having previously occurred only in 1890—when the Baltimore Orioles hosted the Louisville Colonels on September 7 for three games.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1896-major-league-baseball-season] 14 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1899 throughout the world.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-in-baseball] Buck Freeman of the Washington Senators leads all batters with 25 home runs during the regular season, more than double hit by Bobby Wallace of the St.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-in-baseball] Louis Perfectos, who finished with 12 homers.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-in-baseball] Freeman's tally was not surpassed until 1919, when Babe Ruth belted 29 home runs for the Boston Red Sox.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-in-baseball] The National League would remain at eight teams until 1962.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The **1899 major league baseball season** was contested from April 14 through October 15, 1899, and saw the Brooklyn Superbas as the pennant winner of the National League.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The 1899 was the final season of a stable 12-team, eight-season run which saw no expansion or contraction of teams.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Following the end of the season, the National League contracted from 12 to 8 teams, eliminating the Baltimore Orioles, Cleveland Spiders, Louisville Colonels, and Washington Senators.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The elimination of major-league baseball from these cities prompted the minor league Western League to position themselves as a major league in 1901, by beginning a transition from a Midwest-focused league to the nationwide focused American League.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The 1899 season is famous for the Cleveland Spiders finishing with the worst single-season record of all time (minimum 120 games), finishing at a dismal 20–134 (.130), largely due to the fact that the Spiders-owning Robison family bought the St.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Perfectos prior to the 1899 season, then proceeded to move all Cleveland talent to St.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, leaving the Spiders a talent-depleted team.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The only other major-league team of the 19th century with a worse record was the 1884 Wilmington Quicksteps, who entered the unstable single-season Union Association as a late-season replacement for the Philadelphia Keystones and played only 18 games, with a record of 2–16 (.111).
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns renamed as the Brooklyn Superbas and St.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The 1899 schedule consisted of 154 games for the twelve teams of the National League.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other eleven teams in the league.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League in 1892 and the previous season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the final season which saw this format, due to the reduction of teams the following season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 14 featuring four teams.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season on October 15, featuring five teams play in four games (Chicago hosted Louisville and St.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Louis hosted Chicago, while Cincinnati hosted Cleveland in a doubleheader).
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] 20 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Perfectos, New Sportsman's Park, is renamed League Park.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] The home of the Louisville Colonels, Eclipse Park, was destroyed in a fire on August 12, while the team was on a road trip.
[src:cleveland-guardians/1899-major-league-baseball-season] Following their return home, they would have a 12-game homestand from August 22 through September 2 in a partially rebuilt park, before spending the rest of the season on the road.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] The **Cleveland Guardians** are an American professional baseball team based in Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] The Guardians compete in Major League Baseball (MLB) as a member club of the American League (AL) Central Division.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] Since 1994, the team has played its home games at Progressive Field (originally known as Jacobs Field after the team's then-owner).
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] Since their establishment as a Major League franchise in 1901, the team has won 13 Central Division titles, six American League pennants, and two World Series championships (in 1920 and 1948).
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] The team's World Series championship drought since 1948 is the longest active among all 30 current Major League teams.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] The team's name references the *Guardians of Traffic*, eight monolithic 1932 Art Deco sculptures by Henry Hering on the city's Hope Memorial Bridge, which is adjacent to Progressive Field.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] The team's spring training facility is at Goodyear Ballpark in Goodyear, Arizona.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] The franchise originated in 1896 as the **Columbus Buckeyes** (also known as the **Columbus Senators**), a minor league team based in Columbus, Ohio that played in the Western League.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] The team relocated to Grand Rapids, Michigan midseason in 1899, where they were known as the **Grand Rapids Prodigals**.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] In 1900, the franchise moved to Cleveland and was called the **Cleveland Lake Shores**.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] The Western League itself was renamed the American League prior to the 1900 season while continuing its minor league status.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] When the American League declared itself a major league in 1901, Cleveland was one of its eight charter franchises.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] Originally called the **Cleveland Bluebirds** or **Blues**, the team was also unofficially called the **Cleveland Broncos** in 1902.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] Beginning in 1903, the team was named the **Cleveland Napoleons** or **Naps**, after team captain and manager Nap Lajoie.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] Lajoie left after the 1914 season, and club owner Charles Somers requested that baseball writers choose a new name.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] They chose the name **Cleveland Indians**.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] That name stuck and remained in use for more than a century.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] Common nicknames for the Indians were "the Tribe" and "the Wahoos", the latter referencing their longtime logo, Chief Wahoo.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] After the Indians name came under criticism as part of the Native American mascot controversy, the team adopted the current name, Guardians, starting with the 2022 season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] From August 24 to September 14, 2017, the team won 22 consecutive games, the longest winning streak in American League history and the second longest winning streak in MLB history.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] As of the end of the 2025 season, the franchise's overall major league record is 9,940–9,443–91 (.513).
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] According to one historian of baseball, "in 1857, baseball games were a daily spectacle in Cleveland's Public Squares.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] From 1865 to 1868 Forest Citys was an amateur ball club.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] During the 1869 season, Cleveland was among several cities that established professional baseball teams following the success of the 1869 Cincinnati Red Stockings, the first fully professional team.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] In the newspapers before and after 1870, the team was often called the Forest Citys, in the same generic way that the team from Chicago was sometimes called The Chicagos.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] A professional baseball team has played in Cleveland for all but a few years since then.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] In 1871 the Forest Citys joined the new National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA), the first professional league.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] Ultimately, two of the league's western clubs went out of business during the first season and the Chicago Fire left that city's White Stockings impoverished, unable to field a team again until 1874.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] Cleveland was thus the NA's westernmost outpost in 1872, the year the club folded.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] Cleveland played its full schedule to July 19 followed by two games versus Boston in mid-August and disbanded at the end of the season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] In 1876, the National League (NL) supplanted the NA as the major professional league.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] Cleveland was not among its charter members, but by 1879 the league was looking for new entries and the city gained an NL team.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] A new Cleveland Forest Citys were recreated, but by 1882 were known as the Cleveland Blues, because the National League required distinct colors for that season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] The Blues had mediocre records for six seasons and were ruined by a trade war with the Union Association (UA) in 1884, when its three best players (Fred Dunlap, Jack Glasscock, and Jim McCormick) jumped to the UA after being offered higher salaries.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] Cleveland went without major league baseball for two seasons until gaining a team in the American Association (AA) in 1887.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] After the AA's Pittsburgh Alleghenys jumped to the NL, Cleveland followed suit in 1889, as the AA began to crumble.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] The Cleveland ball club, called the Spiders (supposedly inspired by their "skinny and spindly" players), slowly became a power in the league.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] In 1891, the Spiders moved into League Park, which would serve as the home of Cleveland professional baseball for the next 55 years.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] Led by native Ohioan Cy Young, the Spiders became a contender in the mid-1890s, playing in the Temple Cup Series (that era's World Series) twice and winning it in 1895.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] The team began to fade after this success and was dealt a severe blow under the ownership of the Robison brothers.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] Prior to the 1899 season, Frank Robison, the Spiders' owner, bought the St.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] Louis Browns, thus owning two clubs at the same time.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] The Browns were renamed the "Perfectos" and restocked with Cleveland talent.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] Just weeks before the season opener, most of the better Spiders were transferred to St.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] Louis, including three future Hall of Famers: Cy Young, Jesse Burkett and Bobby Wallace.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] The roster maneuvers failed to create a powerhouse Perfectos team, as St.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] Louis finished fifth in both 1899 and 1900.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] The Spiders were left with essentially a minor league lineup and began to lose games at a record pace.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] Drawing almost no fans at home, they ended up playing most of their season on the road, and became known as "The Wanderers".
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] The team ended the season in 12th place, 84 games out of first place, with an all-time worst record of 20–134 (.130 winning percentage).
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] Following the 1899 season, the National League disbanded four teams, including the Spiders franchise.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] The disastrous 1899 season would actually be a step toward a new future for Cleveland fans the next year.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] The Cleveland Infants competed in the Players' League, which was well-attended in some cities, but club owners lacked the confidence to continue beyond the one season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p01] The Cleveland Infants finished with 55 wins and 75 losses, playing their home games at Brotherhood Park.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The origins of the team date back to 1896, when the team was founded as the **Columbus Buckeyes**, a team based in Columbus, Ohio and competing in the Western League.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The club was owned by Tom Loftus, a close friend of both league president Ban Johnson and Charlie Comiskey, owner of the league's St.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In July 1899, the Western League franchise swapped cities midseason with the Grand Rapids franchise of the Interstate League, becoming the **Grand Rapids Prodigals** while remaining in the Western League.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 1900, the team moved to Cleveland and was named the Cleveland Lake Shores, coinciding with Ban Johnson's change of the league name from the Western League to the American League.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 1900, the American League was still considered a minor league.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 1901, the team was called the Cleveland Bluebirds or Blues when the American League broke with the National Agreement and declared itself a competing Major League.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Cleveland franchise was among its eight charter members and is one of four teams that remain in its original city, along with Boston, Chicago, and Detroit.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The new team was owned by coal magnate Charles Somers and tailor Jack Kilfoyl.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Somers, a wealthy industrialist and also co-owner of the Boston Americans, lent money to other team owners, including Connie Mack's Philadelphia Athletics, to keep them and the new league afloat.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Players did not think the name "Bluebirds" was suitable for a baseball team.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Writers frequently shortened it to Cleveland Blues due to the players' all-blue uniforms, but the players did not like this unofficial name either.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The players themselves tried to change the name to Cleveland Bronchos in 1902, but this name never caught on.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Cleveland suffered from financial problems in their first two seasons.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] This led Somers to seriously consider moving to either Pittsburgh or Cincinnati.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Relief came in 1902 as a result of the conflict between the National and American Leagues.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 1901, Napoleon "Nap" Lajoie, the Philadelphia Phillies' star second baseman, jumped to the A's after his contract was capped at $2,400 per year—one of the highest-profile players to jump to the upstart AL.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Phillies subsequently filed an injunction to force Lajoie's return, which was granted by the Pennsylvania Supreme Court.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The injunction appeared to doom any hopes of an early settlement between the warring leagues.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] However, a lawyer discovered that the injunction was only enforceable in the state of Pennsylvania.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Mack, partly to thank Somers for his past financial support, agreed to trade Lajoie to the then-moribund Blues, who offered $25,000 salary over three years.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Due to the injunction, however, Lajoie had to sit out any games played against the A's in Philadelphia.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Lajoie arrived in Cleveland on June 4 and was an immediate hit, drawing 10,000 fans to League Park.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Soon afterward, he was named team captain, and in 1903 the team was called the Cleveland Napoleons or Naps after a newspaper conducted a write-in contest.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Lajoie was named manager in 1905, and the team's fortunes improved somewhat.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] They finished half a game short of the pennant in 1908.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] However, the success did not last and Lajoie resigned during the 1909 season as manager but remained on as a player.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] After that, the team began to unravel, leading Kilfoyl to sell his share of the team to Somers.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Cy Young, who returned to Cleveland in 1909, was ineffective for most of his three remaining years and Addie Joss died from tubercular meningitis prior to the 1911 season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Despite a strong lineup anchored by the potent Lajoie and Shoeless Joe Jackson, poor pitching kept the team below third place for most of the next decade.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] One reporter referred to the team as the Napkins, "because they fold up so easily".
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The team hit bottom in 1914 and 1915, finishing last place both years.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] 1915 brought significant changes to the team.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Lajoie, nearly 40 years old, was no longer a top hitter in the league, batting only .258 in 1914.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] With Lajoie engaged in a feud with manager Joe Birmingham, the team sold Lajoie back to the A's.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] With Lajoie gone, the club needed a new name.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Somers asked the local baseball writers to come up with a new name, and based on their input, the team was renamed the Cleveland Indians.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The name referred to the nickname "Indians" that was applied to the Cleveland Spiders baseball club during the time when Louis Sockalexis, a Native American, played in Cleveland (1897–1899).
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] At the same time, Somers' business ventures began to fail, leaving him deeply in debt.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] With the Indians playing poorly, attendance and revenue suffered.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Somers decided to trade Jackson midway through the 1915 season for two players and $31,500, one of the largest sums paid for a player at the time.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] By 1916, Somers was at the end of his tether, and sold the team to a syndicate headed by Chicago railroad contractor James C.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Manager Lee Fohl, who had taken over in early 1915, acquired two minor league pitchers, Stan Coveleski and Jim Bagby and traded for center fielder Tris Speaker, who was engaged in a salary dispute with the Red Sox.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] All three would ultimately become key players in bringing a championship to Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Speaker took over the reins as player-manager in 1919, and led the team to a championship in 1920.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] On August 16, 1920, the Indians were playing the Yankees at the Polo Grounds in New York.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Shortstop Ray Chapman, who often crowded the plate, was batting against Carl Mays, who had an unusual underhand delivery.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] It was also late in the afternoon and the infield was completely shaded with the center field area (the batters' background) bathed in sunlight.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] As well, at the time, "part of every pitcher's job was to dirty up a new ball the moment it was thrown onto the field.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] By turns, they smeared it with dirt, licorice, tobacco juice; it was deliberately scuffed, sandpapered, scarred, cut, even spiked.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In any case, Chapman did not move reflexively when Mays' pitch came his way.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The pitch hit Chapman in the head, fracturing his skull.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Chapman died the next day, becoming the only player to sustain a fatal injury from a pitched ball.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians, who at the time were locked in a tight three-way pennant race with the Yankees and White Sox, were not slowed down by the death of their teammate.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Rookie Joe Sewell hit .329 after replacing Chapman in the lineup.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In September 1920, the Black Sox Scandal came to a boil.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] With just a few games left in the season, and Cleveland and Chicago neck-and-neck for first place at 94–54 and 95–56 respectively, the Chicago owner suspended eight players.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The White Sox lost two of three in their final series, while Cleveland won four and lost two in their final two series.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Cleveland finished two games ahead of Chicago and three games ahead of the Yankees to win its first pennant, led by Speaker's .388 hitting, Jim Bagby's 30 victories and solid performances from Steve O'Neill and Stan Coveleski.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Cleveland went on to defeat the Brooklyn Robins 5–2 in the World Series for their first title, winning four games in a row after the Robins took a 2–1 Series lead.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Series included three memorable "firsts", all of them in Game 5 at Cleveland, and all by the home team.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In the first inning, right fielder Elmer Smith hit the first Series grand slam.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In the fourth inning, Jim Bagby hit the first Series home run by a pitcher.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In the top of the fifth inning, second baseman Bill Wambsganss executed the first (and only, so far) unassisted triple play in World Series history, in fact, the only Series triple play of any kind.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The team would not reach the heights of 1920 again for 28 years.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Speaker and Coveleski were aging and the Yankees were rising with a new weapon: Babe Ruth and the home run.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] They managed two second-place finishes but spent much of the decade in last place.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] George Pross (Dunn had died in 1922), sold the team to a syndicate headed by Alva Bradley.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians were a middling team by the 1930s, finishing third or fourth most years.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] 1936 brought Cleveland a new superstar in 17-year-old pitcher Bob Feller, who came from Iowa with a dominating fastball.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] That season, Feller set a record with 17 strikeouts in a single game and went on to lead the league in strikeouts from 1938 to 1941.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] On August 20, 1938, Indians catchers Hank Helf and Frank Pytlak set the "all-time altitude mark" by catching baseballs dropped from the 708-foot (216 m) Terminal Tower.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] By 1940, Feller, along with Ken Keltner, Mel Harder and Lou Boudreau, led the Indians to within one game of the pennant.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] However, the team was wracked with dissension, with some players (including Feller and Mel Harder) going so far as to request that Bradley fire manager Ossie Vitt.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Reporters lampooned them as the Cleveland Crybabies.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Feller, who had pitched a no-hitter to open the season and won 27 games, lost the final game of the season to unknown pitcher Floyd Giebell of the Detroit Tigers.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Tigers won the pennant and Giebell never won another major league game.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Cleveland entered 1941 with a young team and a new manager; Roger Peckinpaugh had replaced the despised Vitt; but the team regressed, finishing in fourth.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Cleveland would soon be depleted of two stars.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Hal Trosky retired in 1941 due to migraine headaches and Bob Feller enlisted in the Navy two days after the Attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Starting third baseman Ken Keltner and outfielder Ray Mack were both drafted in 1945 taking two more starters out of the lineup.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 1946, Bill Veeck formed an investment group that purchased the Cleveland Indians from Bradley's group for a reported $1.6 million.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Among the investors was Bob Hope, who had grown up in Cleveland, and former Tigers slugger, Hank Greenberg.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] A former owner of a minor league franchise in Milwaukee, Veeck brought to Cleveland a gift for promotion.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] At one point, Veeck hired rubber-faced Max Patkin, the "Clown Prince of Baseball" as a coach.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Patkin's appearance in the coaching box was the sort of promotional stunt that delighted fans but infuriated the American League front office.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Recognizing that he had acquired a solid team, Veeck soon abandoned the aging, small and lightless League Park to take up full-time residence in massive Cleveland Municipal Stadium.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians had briefly moved from League Park to Municipal Stadium in mid-1932, but moved back to League Park due to complaints about the cavernous environment.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] From 1937 onward, however, the Indians began playing an increasing number of games at Municipal, until by 1940 they played most of their home slate there.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] League Park was mostly demolished in 1951, but has since been rebuilt as a recreational park.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Making the most of the cavernous stadium, Veeck had a portable center field fence installed, which he could move in or out depending on how the distance favored the Indians against their opponents in a given series.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The fence moved as much as 15 feet (5 m) between series opponents.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Following the 1947 season, the American League countered with a rule change that fixed the distance of an outfield wall for the duration of a season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The massive stadium did, however, permit the Indians to set the then-record for the largest crowd to see a Major League baseball game.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] On October 10, 1948, Game 5 of the World Series against the Boston Braves drew over 84,000.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The record stood until the Los Angeles Dodgers drew a crowd in excess of 92,500 to watch Game 5 of the 1959 World Series at the Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum against the Chicago White Sox.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Under Veeck's leadership, one of Cleveland's most significant achievements was breaking the color barrier in the American League by signing Larry Doby, formerly a player for the Negro league's Newark Eagles in 1947, 11 weeks after Jackie Robinson signed with the Dodgers.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Similar to Robinson, Doby battled racism on and off the field but posted a .301 batting average in 1948, his first full season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] A power-hitting center fielder, Doby led the American League twice in homers.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 1948, needing pitching for the stretch run of the pennant race, Veeck turned to the Negro leagues again and signed pitching great Satchel Paige amid much controversy.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Barred from Major League Baseball during his prime, Veeck's signing of the aging star in 1948 was viewed by many as another publicity stunt.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] At an official age of 42, Paige became the oldest rookie in Major League baseball history, and the first black pitcher.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Paige ended the year with a 6–1 record with a 2.48 ERA, 45 strikeouts and two shutouts.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 1948, veterans Boudreau, Keltner, and Joe Gordon had career offensive seasons, while newcomers Doby and Gene Bearden also had standout seasons.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The team went down to the wire with the Boston Red Sox, winning a one-game playoff, the first in American League history, to go to the World Series.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In the series, the Indians defeated the Boston Braves four games to two for their first championship in 28 years.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Boudreau won the American League MVP Award.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians appeared in a film the following year titled *The Kid From Cleveland*, in which Veeck had an interest.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The film portrayed the team helping out a "troubled teenaged fan" and featured many members of the Indians organization.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] However, filming during the season cost the players valuable rest days leading to fatigue towards the end of the season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] That season, Cleveland again contended before falling to third place.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] On September 23, 1949, Bill Veeck and the Indians buried their 1948 pennant in center field the day after they were mathematically eliminated from the pennant race.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Later in 1949, Veeck's first wife (who had a half-stake in Veeck's share of the team) divorced him.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] With most of his money tied up in the Indians, Veeck was forced to sell the team to a syndicate headed by insurance magnate Ellis Ryan.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Ryan was forced out in 1953 in favor of Myron Wilson, who in turn gave way to William Daley in 1956.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Despite this turnover in the ownership, a powerhouse team composed of Feller, Doby, Minnie Miñoso, Luke Easter, Bobby Ávila, Al Rosen, Early Wynn, Bob Lemon, and Mike Garcia continued to contend through the early 1950s.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] However, Cleveland only won a single pennant in the decade, in 1954, finishing second to the New York Yankees five times.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The winningest season in franchise history came in 1954, when the Indians finished the season with a record of 111–43 (.721).
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] That mark set an American League record for wins that stood for 44 years until the Yankees won 114 games in 1998 (a 162-game regular season record of 114-48/.704).
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians' 1954 winning percentage of .721 is still an American League record.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians returned to the World Series to face the New York Giants.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The team could not bring home the title, however, ultimately being upset by the Giants in a sweep.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The series was notable for Willie Mays' over-the-shoulder catch off the bat of Vic Wertz in Game 1.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Cleveland remained a talented team throughout the remainder of the decade, finishing in second place in 1959, George Strickland's last full year in the majors.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] From 1960 to 1993, the Indians managed one third-place finish (in 1968) and six fourth-place finishes (in 1960, 1974, 1975, 1976, 1990, and 1992) but spent the rest of the time at or near the bottom of the standings, including four seasons with over 100 losses (1971, 1985, 1987, 1991).
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians hired general manager Frank Lane, known as "Trader" Lane, away from the St.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Lane over the years had gained a reputation as a GM who loved to make deals.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] With the White Sox, Lane had made over 100 trades involving over 400 players in seven years.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Louis, he traded away Red Schoendienst and Harvey Haddix.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Lane summed up his philosophy when he said that the only deals he regretted were the ones that he did not make.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] One of Lane's early trades in Cleveland was to send Roger Maris to the Kansas City Athletics in the middle of 1958.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Indians executive Hank Greenberg was not happy about the trade and neither was Maris, who said that he could not stand Lane.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] After Maris broke Babe Ruth's home run record, Lane defended himself by saying he still would have done the deal because Maris was unknown and he received good ballplayers in exchange.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] After the Maris trade, Lane acquired 25-year-old Norm Cash from the White Sox for Minnie Miñoso and then traded him to Detroit before he ever played a game for the Indians; Cash went on to hit over 350 home runs for the Tigers.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians received Steve Demeter in the deal, who had only five at-bats for Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 1960, Lane made the trade that would define his tenure in Cleveland when he dealt slugging right fielder and fan favorite Rocky Colavito to the Detroit Tigers for Harvey Kuenn just before Opening Day in 1960.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] It was a blockbuster trade that swapped the 1959 AL home run co-champion (Colavito) for the AL batting champion (Kuenn).
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] After the trade, however, Colavito hit over 30 home runs four times and made three All-Star teams for Detroit and Kansas City before returning to Cleveland in 1965.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Kuenn, on the other hand, played only one season for the Indians before departing for San Francisco in a trade for an aging Johnny Antonelli and Willie Kirkland.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] *Akron Beacon Journal* columnist Terry Pluto documented the decades of woe that followed the trade in his book *The Curse of Rocky Colavito*.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Despite being attached to the curse, Colavito said that he never placed a curse on the Indians but that the trade was prompted by a salary dispute with Lane.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Lane also engineered a unique trade of managers in mid-season 1960, sending Joe Gordon to the Tigers in exchange for Jimmy Dykes.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Lane left the team in 1961, but ill-advised trades continued.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 1965, the Indians traded pitcher Tommy John, who would go on to win 288 games in his career, and 1966 Rookie of the Year Tommy Agee to the White Sox to get Colavito back.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] However, Indians' pitchers set numerous strikeout records.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] They led the league in K's every year from 1963 to 1968, and narrowly missed in 1969.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The 1964 staff was the first to amass 1,100 strikeouts, and in 1968, they were the first to collect more strikeouts than hits allowed.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The 1970s were not much better, with the Indians trading away several future stars, including Graig Nettles, Dennis Eckersley, Buddy Bell and 1971 Rookie of the Year Chris Chambliss, for a number of players who made no impact.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Constant ownership changes did not help the Indians.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 1963, Daley's syndicate sold the team to a group headed by general manager Gabe Paul.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Three years later, Paul sold the Indians to Vernon Stouffer, of the Stouffer Corporation empire.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Prior to Stouffer's purchase, the team was rumored to be relocated due to poor attendance.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Despite the potential for a financially strong owner, Stouffer had some non-baseball related financial setbacks and, consequently, the team was cash-poor.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In order to solve some financial problems, Stouffer had made an agreement to play a minimum of 30 home games in New Orleans with a view to a possible move there.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] After rejecting an offer from George Steinbrenner and former Indian Al Rosen, Stouffer sold the team in 1972 to a group led by Cleveland Cavaliers and Cleveland Barons owner Nick Mileti.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Steinbrenner went on to buy the New York Yankees in 1973.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Only five years later, Mileti's group sold the team for $11 million to a syndicate headed by trucking magnate Steve O'Neill and including former general manager and owner Gabe Paul.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] O'Neill's death in 1983 led to the team going on the market once more.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] O'Neill's nephew Patrick O'Neill did not find a buyer until real estate magnates Richard E. and David H.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The team was unable to move out of last place, with losing seasons between 1969 and 1975.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] One highlight was the acquisition of Gaylord Perry in 1972.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians traded fireballer "Sudden Sam" McDowell for Perry, who became the first Indian pitcher to win the Cy Young Award.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 1975, Cleveland broke another color barrier with the hiring of Frank Robinson as Major League Baseball's first African American manager.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Robinson served as player-manager and provided a franchise highlight when he hit a pinch-hit home run on Opening Day.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] But the high-profile signing of Wayne Garland, a 20-game winner in Baltimore, proved to be a disaster after Garland suffered from shoulder problems and went 28–48 over five years.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The team failed to improve with Robinson as manager and he was fired in 1977.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 1977, pitcher Dennis Eckersley threw a no-hitter against the California Angels.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The next season, he was traded to the Boston Red Sox where he won 20 games in 1978 and another 17 in 1979.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The 1970s also featured the infamous Ten Cent Beer Night at Cleveland Municipal Stadium.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The ill-conceived promotion at a 1974 game against the Texas Rangers ended in a riot by fans and a forfeit by the Indians.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] There were more bright spots in the 1980s.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In May 1981, Len Barker threw a perfect game against the Toronto Blue Jays, joining Addie Joss as the only other Indian pitcher to do so.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] "Super Joe" Charboneau won the American League Rookie of the Year award.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Charboneau was out of baseball by 1983 due to back injuries and Barker, who was also hampered by injuries, never became a consistently dominant starting pitcher.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Eventually, the Indians traded Barker to the Atlanta Braves for Brett Butler and Brook Jacoby, who became mainstays of the team for the remainder of the decade.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Butler and Jacoby were joined by Joe Carter, Mel Hall, Julio Franco and Cory Snyder, bringing new hope to fans in the late 1980s.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Cleveland's struggles over the 30-year span were highlighted in the 1989 film *Major League*, which comically depicted a hapless Cleveland ball club going from worst to first by the end of the film.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Throughout the 1980s, the Indians' owners had pushed for a new stadium.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Cleveland Stadium had been a symbol of the Indians' glory years in the 1940s and 1950s.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] However, during the lean years even crowds of 40,000 were swallowed up by the cavernous environment.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The old stadium was not aging gracefully; chunks of concrete were falling off in sections and the old wooden pilings were petrifying.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 1984, a proposal for a $150 million domed stadium was defeated in a referendum 2–1.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Finally, in May 1990, Cuyahoga County voters passed an excise tax on sales of alcohol and cigarettes in the county.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The tax proceeds were to be used for financing the construction of the Gateway Sports and Entertainment Complex, which would include Jacobs Field for the Indians and Gund Arena for the Cleveland Cavs basketball team.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The team's fortunes started to turn in 1989, ironically with a very unpopular trade.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The team sent power-hitting outfielder Joe Carter to the San Diego Padres for two unproven players, Sandy Alomar Jr. and Carlos Baerga.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Alomar made an immediate impact, not only being elected to the All-Star team but also winning Cleveland's fourth Rookie of the Year award and a Gold Glove.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Baerga became a three-time All-Star with consistent offensive production.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Indians general manager John Hart made a number of moves that finally brought success to the team.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 1991, he hired former Indian Mike Hargrove to manage and traded catcher Eddie Taubensee to the Houston Astros who, with a surplus of outfielders, were willing to part with Kenny Lofton.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Lofton finished second in AL Rookie of the Year balloting with a .285 average and 66 stolen bases.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians were named "Organization of the Year" by *Baseball America* in 1992, in response to the appearance of offensive bright spots and an improving farm system.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The team suffered a tragedy during spring training of 1993, when a boat carrying pitchers Steve Olin, Tim Crews, and Bob Ojeda crashed into a pier.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Olin and Crews were killed, and Ojeda was seriously injured.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] (Ojeda missed most of the season, and retired the following year).
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] By the end of the 1993 season, the team was in transition, leaving Cleveland Stadium and fielding a talented nucleus of young players.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Many of those players came from the Indians' new AAA farm team, the Charlotte Knights, who won the International League title that year.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Indians General Manager John Hart and team owner Richard E.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Jacobs managed to turn the team's fortunes around.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians opened Jacobs Field in 1994 with the aim of improving on the prior season's sixth-place finish.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians were only one game behind the division-leading Chicago White Sox on August 12 when a players strike wiped out the rest of the season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Having contended for the division in the aborted 1994 season, Cleveland sprinted to a 100–44 record (the season was shortened by 18 games due to player/owner negotiations) in 1995, winning its first-ever divisional title.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Veterans Dennis Martínez, Orel Hershiser and Eddie Murray combined with a young core of players including Omar Vizquel, Albert Belle, Jim Thome, Manny Ramírez, Kenny Lofton and Charles Nagy to lead the league in team batting average as well as team ERA.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] After defeating the Boston Red Sox in the Division Series and the Seattle Mariners in the ALCS, Cleveland clinched the American League pennant and a World Series berth, for the first time since 1954.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The World Series ended in disappointment, however: the Indians fell in six games to the Atlanta Braves.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Tickets for every Indians home game sold out several months before opening day in 1996.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians repeated as AL Central champions but lost to the wild card Baltimore Orioles in the Division Series.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 1997, Cleveland started slow but finished with an 86–75 record.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Taking their third consecutive AL Central title, the Indians defeated the New York Yankees in the Division Series, 3–2.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] After defeating the Baltimore Orioles in the ALCS, Cleveland went on to face the Florida Marlins in the World Series that featured the coldest game in World Series history.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] With the series tied after Game 6, the Indians went into the ninth inning of Game Seven with a 2–1 lead, but closer José Mesa allowed the Marlins to tie the game.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In the eleventh inning, Édgar Rentería drove in the winning run giving the Marlins their first championship.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Cleveland became the first team to lose the World Series after carrying the lead into the ninth inning of the seventh game.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 1998, the Indians made the postseason for the fourth straight year.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] After defeating the wild-card Boston Red Sox 3–1 in the Division Series, Cleveland lost the 1998 ALCS in six games to the New York Yankees, who had come into the postseason with a then-AL record 114 wins in the regular season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] For the 1999 season, Cleveland added relief pitcher Ricardo Rincón and second baseman Roberto Alomar, brother of catcher Sandy Alomar Jr., and won the Central Division title for the fifth consecutive year.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The team scored 1,009 runs, becoming the first (and to date only) team since the 1950 Boston Red Sox to score more than 1,000 runs in a season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] This time, Cleveland did not make it past the first round, losing the Division Series to the Red Sox, despite taking a 2–0 lead in the series.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In game three, Indians starter Dave Burba went down with an injury in the 4th inning.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Four pitchers, including presumed game four starter Jaret Wright, surrendered nine runs in relief.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Without a long reliever or emergency starter on the playoff roster, Hargrove started both Bartolo Colón and Charles Nagy in games four and five on only three days rest.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians lost game four 23–7 and game five 12–8.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Four days later, Hargrove was dismissed as manager.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 2000, the Indians had a 44–42 start, but caught fire after the All Star break and went 46–30 the rest of the way to finish 90–72.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The team had one of the league's best offenses that year and a defense that yielded three gold gloves.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] However, they ended up five games behind the Chicago White Sox in the Central division and missed the wild card by one game to the Seattle Mariners.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Mid-season trades brought Bob Wickman and Jake Westbrook to Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] After the season, free-agent outfielder Manny Ramírez departed for the Boston Red Sox.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Dolan bought the Indians for $320 million from Richard E.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Jacobs, who, along with his late brother David, had paid $45 million for the club in 1986.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The sale set a record at the time for the sale of a baseball franchise.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] After the departures of Ramírez and Sandy Alomar Jr., the Indians signed Ellis Burks and former MVP Juan González, who helped the team win the Central division with a 91–71 record.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] One of the highlights came on August 5, when the Indians completed the biggest comeback in MLB History.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Cleveland rallied to close a 14–2 deficit in the seventh inning to defeat the Seattle Mariners 15–14 in 11 innings.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Mariners, who won an MLB record-tying 116 games that season, had a strong bullpen, and Indians manager Charlie Manuel had already pulled many of his starters with the game seemingly out of reach.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Seattle and Cleveland met in the first round of the postseason; however, the Mariners won the series 3–2.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In the 2001–02 offseason, GM John Hart resigned and his assistant, Mark Shapiro, took the reins.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Shapiro moved to rebuild by dealing aging veterans for younger talent.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] He traded Roberto Alomar to the New York Mets for a package that included outfielder Matt Lawton and prospects Alex Escobar and Billy Traber.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] When the team fell out of contention in mid-2002, Shapiro fired manager Charlie Manuel and traded pitching ace Bartolo Colón for prospects Brandon Phillips, Cliff Lee, and Grady Sizemore; acquired Travis Hafner from the Rangers for Ryan Drese and Einar Díaz; and picked up Coco Crisp from the St.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Louis Cardinals for aging starter Chuck Finley.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Jim Thome left after the season, going to the Phillies for a larger contract.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Young Indians teams finished far out of contention in 2002 and 2003 under new manager Eric Wedge.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] They posted strong offensive numbers in 2004, but continued to struggle with a bullpen that blew more than 20 saves.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] A highlight of the season was a 22–0 victory over the New York Yankees on August 31, one of the worst defeats suffered by the Yankees in team history.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In early 2005, the offense got off to a poor start.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] After a brief July slump, the Indians caught fire in August, and cut a 15.5 game deficit in the Central Division down to 1.5 games.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] However, the season came to an end as the Indians went on to lose six of their last seven games, five of them by one run, missing the playoffs by only two games.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Shapiro was named Executive of the Year in 2005.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The next season, the club made several roster changes, while retaining its nucleus of young players.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The off-season was highlighted by the acquisition of top prospect Andy Marte from the Boston Red Sox.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians had a solid offensive season, led by career years from Travis Hafner and Grady Sizemore.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Hafner, despite missing the last month of the season, tied the single season grand slam record of six, which was set in 1987 by Don Mattingly.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Despite the solid offensive performance, the bullpen struggled with 23 blown saves (a Major League worst), and the Indians finished a disappointing fourth.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 2007, Shapiro signed veteran help for the bullpen and outfield in the offseason.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Veterans Aaron Fultz and Joe Borowski joined Rafael Betancourt in the Indians bullpen.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians improved significantly over the prior year and went into the All-Star break in second place.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The team brought back Kenny Lofton for his third stint with the team in late July.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians finished with a 96–66 record tied with the Red Sox for best in baseball, their seventh Central Division title in 13 years and their first postseason trip since 2001.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians began their playoff run by defeating the Yankees in the ALDS three games to one.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] This series will be most remembered for the swarm of bugs that overtook the field in the later innings of Game Two.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] They also jumped out to a three-games-to-one lead over the Red Sox in the ALCS.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The season ended in disappointment when Boston swept the final three games to advance to the 2007 World Series.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Despite the loss, Cleveland players took home a number of awards.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Grady Sizemore, who had a .995 fielding percentage and only two errors in 405 chances, won the Gold Glove award, Cleveland's first since 2001.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Indians Pitcher CC Sabathia won the second Cy Young Award in team history with a 19–7 record, a 3.21 ERA and an MLB-leading 241 innings pitched.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Eric Wedge was awarded the first Manager of the Year Award in team history.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Shapiro was named to his second Executive of the Year in 2007.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians struggled during the 2008 season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Injuries to sluggers Travis Hafner and Victor Martinez, as well as starting pitchers Jake Westbrook and Fausto Carmona led to a poor start.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians, falling to last place for a short time in June and July, traded CC Sabathia to the Milwaukee Brewers for prospects Matt LaPorta, Rob Bryson, and Michael Brantley. and traded starting third baseman Casey Blake for catching prospect Carlos Santana.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Pitcher Cliff Lee went 22–3 with an ERA of 2.54 and earned the AL Cy Young Award.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Grady Sizemore had a career year, winning a Gold Glove Award and a Silver Slugger Award, and the Indians finished with a record of 81–81.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Prospects for the 2009 season dimmed early when the Indians ended May with a record of 22–30.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians finished the season tied for fourth in their division, with a record of 65–97.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The team announced on September 30, 2009, that Eric Wedge and all of the team's coaching staff were released at the end of the 2009 season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Manny Acta was hired as the team's 40th manager on October 25, 2009.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] On February 18, 2010, it was announced that Shapiro (following the end of the 2010 season) would be promoted to team President, with current President Paul J.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Dolan becoming the new Chairman/CEO, and longtime Shapiro assistant Chris Antonetti filling the GM role.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] On January 18, 2011, longtime popular former first baseman and manager Mike Hargrove was brought in as a special adviser.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians started the 2011 season strong – going 30–15 in their first 45 games and seven games ahead of the Detroit Tigers for first place.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Injuries led to a slump where the Indians fell out of first place.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Many minor leaguers such as Jason Kipnis and Lonnie Chisenhall got opportunities to fill in for the injuries.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The biggest news of the season came on July 30 when the Indians traded four prospects for Colorado Rockies star pitcher, Ubaldo Jiménez.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians sent their top two pitchers in the minors, Alex White and Drew Pomeranz along with Joe Gardner and Matt McBride.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] On August 25, the Indians signed the team leader in home runs, Jim Thome off of waivers.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] He made his first appearance in an Indians uniform since he left Cleveland after the 2002 season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] To honor Thome, the Indians placed him at his original position, third base, for one pitch against the Minnesota Twins on September 25.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] It was his first appearance at third base since 1996, and his last for Cleveland.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians finished the season in 2nd place, 15 games behind the division champion Tigers.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians broke Progressive Field's Opening Day attendance record with 43,190 against the Toronto Blue Jays on April 5, 2012.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The game went 16 innings, setting the MLB Opening Day record, and lasted 5 hours and 14 minutes.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] On September 27, 2012, with six games left in the Indians' 2012 season, Manny Acta was fired; Sandy Alomar Jr. was named interim manager for the remainder of the season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] On October 6, the Indians announced that Terry Francona, who managed the Boston Red Sox to five playoff appearances and two World Series between 2004 and 2011, would take over as manager for 2013.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians entered the 2013 season following an active offseason of dramatic roster turnover.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Key acquisitions included free agent 1B/OF Nick Swisher and CF Michael Bourn.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The team added prized right-handed pitching prospect Trevor Bauer, OF Drew Stubbs, and relief pitchers Bryan Shaw and Matt Albers in a three-way trade with the Arizona Diamondbacks and Cincinnati Reds that sent RF Shin-Soo Choo to the Reds, and Tony Sipp to the Arizona Diamondbacks.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Other notable additions included utility man Mike Avilés, catcher Yan Gomes, designated hitter Jason Giambi, and starting pitcher Scott Kazmir.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The 2013 Indians increased their win total by 24 over 2012 (from 68 to 92), finishing in second place, one game behind Detroit in the Central division, but securing the number one seed in the American League Wild Card Standings.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In their first postseason appearance since 2007, Cleveland lost the 2013 American League Wild Card Game 4–0 at home to Tampa Bay.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Francona was recognized for the turnaround with the 2013 American League Manager of the Year Award.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] With an 85–77 record, the 2014 Indians had consecutive winning seasons for the first time since 1999–2001, but they were eliminated from playoff contention during the last week of the season and finished third in the AL Central.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 2015, after struggling through the first half of the season, the Indians finished 81–80 for their third consecutive winning season, which the team had not done since 1999–2001.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] For the second straight year, the Tribe finished third in the Central and was eliminated from the Wild Card race during the last week of the season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Following the departure of longtime team executive Mark Shapiro on October 6, the Indians promoted GM Chris Antonetti to President of Baseball Operations, assistant general manager Mike Chernoff to GM, and named Derek Falvey as assistant GM.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Falvey was later hired by the Minnesota Twins in 2016, becoming their President of Baseball Operations.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians set what was then a franchise record for longest winning streak when they won their 14th consecutive game, a 2–1 win over the Toronto Blue Jays in 19 innings on July 1, 2016, at Rogers Centre.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The team clinched the Central Division pennant on September 26, their eighth division title overall and first since 2007, as well as returning to the playoffs for the first time since 2013.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] They finished the regular season at 94–67, marking their fourth straight winning season, a feat not accomplished since the 1990s and early 2000s.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] It marked the first appearance for the Indians in the World Series since 1997 and first for the Cubs since 1945.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians took a 3–1 series lead following a victory in Game 4 at Wrigley Field, but the Cubs rallied to take the final three games and won the series 4 games to 3.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians' 2016 success led to Francona winning his second AL Manager of the Year Award with the club.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] From August 24 through September 15 during the 2017 season, the Indians set a new American League record by winning 22 games in a row.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] On September 28, the Indians won their 100th game of the season, marking only the third time in history the team has reached that milestone.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] They finished the regular season with 102 wins, second-most in team history (behind 1954's 111 win team).
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Indians earned the AL Central title for the second consecutive year, along with home-field advantage throughout the American League playoffs, but they lost the 2017 ALDS to the Yankees 3–2 after being up 2–0.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 2018, the Indians won their third consecutive AL Central crown with a 91–71 record, but were swept in the 2018 American League Division Series by the Houston Astros, who outscored Cleveland 21–6.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 2019, despite a two-game improvement, the Indians missed the playoffs as they trailed three games behind the Tampa Bay Rays for the second AL Wild Card berth.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] During the 2020 season (shortened to 60 games because of the COVID-19 pandemic), the Indians were 35–25, finishing second behind the Minnesota Twins in the AL Central, but qualified for the expanded playoffs.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In the best-of-three AL Wild Card Series, the Indians were swept by the New York Yankees, ending their season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Dolan, who owned the team since the year 2000 and served as the longest owner in the history of the Cleveland franchise, died.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] His son Paul, who is listed as the team's "Owner/CEO/Chairman," has held ownership duties over the team since 2013, and is also the only of Larry J.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Dolan's children who has held major leadership roles over the Guardians.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In May 2026, Cleveland Heights native and NFL football player Travis Kelce became a minority owner.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] On December 18, 2020, the team announced that the Indians name and logo would be dropped after the 2021 season, later revealing the replacement to be the Guardians.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In their first season as the Guardians, the team won the 2022 AL Central Division crown, marking the 11th division title in franchise history.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In the best-of-three AL Wild Card Series, the Guardians won the series against the Tampa Bay Rays 2–0, to advance to the AL Division Series.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Guardians lost the series to the New York Yankees 3–2, ending their season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In June 2022, sports investor David Blitzer bought a 25% stake in the franchise with an option to acquire controlling interest in 2028.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Following Francona's retirement at the end of the 2023 season, the Guardians named Stephen Vogt as their new manager on November 6, 2023.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Vogt would lead the Guardians to a bounce-back season, winning the AL Central with a 92–69 record.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Guardians would beat their AL Central rival the Detroit Tigers in the AL Division Series in five games, but would lose to the New York Yankees in the AL Pennant in five games.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 2025, Vogt led the team back from a 15.5 game deficit in July, to overtake Detroit and win the second straight AL Central title under his watch.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The rivalry with fellow Ohio team the Cincinnati Reds is known as the Battle of Ohio or Buckeye Series and features the Ohio Cup trophy for the winner.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Prior to 1997, the winner of the cup was determined by an annual pre-season baseball game, played each year at minor-league Cooper Stadium in the state capital of Columbus, and staged just days before the start of each new Major League Baseball season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] A total of eight Ohio Cup games were played, with the Guardians winning six of them.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] It ended with the start of interleague play in 1997.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The winner of the game each year was awarded the Ohio Cup in postgame ceremonies.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Ohio Cup was a favorite among baseball fans in Columbus, with attendances regularly topping 15,000.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Since 1997, the two teams have played each other as part of the regular season, with the exception of 2002.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Ohio Cup was reintroduced in 2008 and is presented to the team who wins the most games in the series that season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Initially, the teams played one three-game series per season, meeting in Cleveland in 1997 and Cincinnati the following year.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The teams have played two series per season against each other since 1999, with the exception of 2002, one at each ballpark.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] A format change in 2013 made each series two games, except in years when the AL and NL Central divisions meet in interleague play, where it is usually extended to three games per series.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] As of June 2025, the Guardians lead the series 77–64.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Guardians share a rivalry with the Detroit Tigers fueled by geographic proximity between the two cities, and elements from the intense rivalry between Michigan and Ohio State.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The rivalry with came to a head on August 7, 2013, with the teams first and second in the AL Central standings.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Many Tigers fans who made the short trip to Cleveland started a "Let's go Tigers!" chant while the game was tied in the nith inning.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Cleveland fans countered with a "Detroit's bankrupt!" chant, in reference to the city's 2013 bankruptcy.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Footage of the chants from SportsTime Ohio circulated online, with many baseball fans on social media criticizing Cleveland fans for the chant due to the circumstances of Detroit's financial situation.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Tigers ended up defeating Cleveland 6–5 in 14 innings.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The two teams have played almost evenly over their 125-year history with Detroit holding a narrow 1,168–1,167 lead.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The teams have met twice in the postseason, with Cleveland winning the 2024 AL Division Series and Detroit winning the 2025 AL Wild Card Series.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The Chicago White Sox are another rival, dating back to the 1959 season, when the Sox slipped past the Indians to win the AL pennant.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] The rivalry intensified when both clubs were moved to the newly created AL Central in 1994.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] During that season, the two teams challenged for the division title, with the Indians one game back of Chicago when the season ended in August due to the players' strike.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] During a game in Chicago, the White Sox confiscated Albert Belle's corked bat, followed by an attempt by Indians pitcher Jason Grimsley to crawl through the Comiskey Park clubhouse ceiling to retrieve it.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Belle later signed with the White Sox in 1997, adding additional intensity to the rivalry.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] In 2005, the White Sox led the division by 15 games in July, only to see the Indians trim the lead to a single game late in the season.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] However, the White Sox swept a three-game series to end the season to win the division by six games; the Sox later won that year's World Series.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] On August 5, 2023, Cleveland third baseman José Ramírez and Chicago shortstop Tim Anderson instigated a bench-clearing brawl after Anderson applied a tag to Ramírez.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Anderson then attempted to punch Ramírez, after which Ramírez wound up knocking Anderson to the ground with a right hook.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p02] Anderson and Ramírez were suspended five and two games, respectively, for their roles in the brawl.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] The official team colors are navy blue, red, and white.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] The primary home uniform is white with red and navy blue piping around each sleeve.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] Across the front of the jersey in script font is the word "Guardians" in red with a navy blue outline, with navy blue undershirts, belts, and socks.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] The alternate home jersey is red with a navy blue "diamond C" font "Guardians" trimmed in white on the front, and white and navy blue piping on both sleeves, with navy blue undershirts, belts, and socks.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] In 2024, the team introduced "City Connect" uniforms, primarily (but not exclusively) worn on Friday home dates.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] The standard home cap is red with a navy blue bill, and features a navy blue "diamond C" on the front and is worn with the primary white uniforms.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] With the alternate red jerseys, the cap is navy blue with a red bill and red "diamond C".
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] The "City Connect" home cap is similar to the alternate cap with the exception of the front section over the bill being white.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] The primary road uniform is gray, with "Cleveland" in navy blue "diamond C" letters, trimmed in red across the front of the jersey, red and navy blue piping around the sleeves, and navy blue undershirts, belts, and socks.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] The alternate road jersey is navy blue with a red "diamond C" trimmed in white on the front of the jersey, red and white piping around the sleeves, and navy blue undershirts, belts, and socks.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] With either road jersey, the team wears a navy blue cap with a red bill and red "diamond C".
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] For all games, the team uses a navy blue batting helmet with a red "diamond C" on the front.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] All jerseys (sans the "City Connect" version) feature the "winged G" logo on one sleeve, and every jersey has a patch from Marathon Petroleum – in a sponsorship deal lasting through the 2026 season – on the other.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] The sleeve featuring the Marathon logo depends on how the player bats – left handed hitters have it on their right sleeve, as that is the arm facing the main TV camera when he bats, and vice versa for right handed batters.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] The club name and its cartoon logo have been criticized for perpetuating Native American stereotypes.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] In 1997 and 1998, protesters were arrested after effigies were burned.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] Charges were dismissed in the 1997 case, and were not filed in the 1998 case.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] Protesters arrested in the 1998 incident subsequently fought and lost a lawsuit alleging that their First Amendment rights had been violated.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] Bud Selig (then–commissioner of baseball) said in 2014 that he had never received a complaint about the logo.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] He has heard that there are some protesting against the mascots, but individual teams such as the Indians and Atlanta Braves, whose name was also criticized for similar reasons, should make their own decisions.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] An organized group consisting of Native Americans, which had protested for many years, protested Chief Wahoo on Opening Day 2015, noting that this was the 100th anniversary since the team became the Indians.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] Owner Paul Dolan, while stating his respect for the critics, said he mainly heard from fans who wanted to keep Chief Wahoo, and had no plans to change.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] On January 29, 2018, Major League Baseball announced that Chief Wahoo would be removed from the Indians' uniforms for the 2019 season, stating that the logo was no longer appropriate for on-field use.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] The block "C" was promoted to the primary logo; at the time, there were no plans to change the team's name.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] In 2020, protests over the murder of George Floyd, a black man, by a Minneapolis police officer, led the United States into a period of social changes.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] This made Dolan reconsider use of the Indians name.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] On December 13, 2020, it was reported that the Indians name would be dropped after the 2021 season out of respect for the Native American community.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] It had been hinted by the team that they may move forward without a replacement name (in a similar manner to the Washington Football Team, which used its name for two years until being named the Washington Commanders).
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] It was announced via Twitter on July 23, 2021, that the team will be named the Guardians, after the *Guardians of Traffic*, eight large Art Deco statues on the Hope Memorial Bridge, located close to Progressive Field.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] The club, however, found itself amid a trademark dispute with a men's roller derby team called the Cleveland Guardians.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] The Cleveland Guardians roller derby team has competed in the Men's Roller Derby Association since 2016.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] In addition, two other entities have attempted to preempt the team's use of the trademark by filing their own registrations with the U.S.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] The roller derby team filed a federal lawsuit in the U.S.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] District Court for the Northern District of Ohio on October 27, 2021, seeking to block the baseball team's name change.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] On November 16, 2021, the lawsuit was resolved, and both teams were allowed to continue using the Guardians name.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] The name change from Indians to Guardians became official on November 19, 2021.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] Cleveland radio stations WTAM (1100 AM and 106.9 FM) and WMMS (100.7 FM), both owned by iHeartMedia, serve as flagship stations for the Cleveland Guardians Radio Network.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] Frick Award winner Tom Hamilton and Jim Rosenhaus comprise the announcing team and call all games on-site.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] Fellow sister station WARF (1350 AM) - while primarily an English language station - serves as the team's Spanish flagship, airing broadcasts of home games.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] Rafa Hernández-Brito serves as the primary Spanish announcer, alongside analyst and former Indian Carlos Baerga.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] Regular season games not broadcast by MLB's national TV partners are shown exclusively on Guardians TV, operated by MLB Local Media, which launched on February 11, 2025.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] Cleveland NBC affiliate WKYC channel 3 simulcasts select games, plus airs a weekly team centered sportscast titled *Guardians Tonight* Sunday nights.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] Guardians TV airs on cable systems throughout Northeast Ohio, as well as functioning as a streaming service.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] Notable former broadcasters include Tom Manning, Jack Graney (the first ex-baseball player to become a play-by-play announcer), Ken Coleman, Joe Castiglione, Van Patrick, Nev Chandler, Bruce Drennan, Jim "Mudcat" Grant, Rocky Colavito, Dan Coughlin, and Jim Donovan.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] Previous broadcasters who have had lengthy tenures with the team include Joe Tait (15 seasons between TV and radio), Jack Corrigan (18 seasons on TV), Ford C.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] Frick Award winner Jimmy Dudley (19 seasons on radio), Mike Hegan (23 seasons between TV and radio), and Herb Score (34 seasons between TV and radio).
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] (*) – Inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame as an Indian/Nap.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] In July 2022, in honor of the 75th anniversary of Larry Doby becoming the AL's first black player, a mural was added to the exterior of Progressive Field, honoring players who were viewed as barrier breakers that played for the Indians/Guardians.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] The mural features Doby, Frank Robinson, and Satchel Paige.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] The Cleveland Guardians farm system consists of seven minor league affiliates.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] (*): There were no fans allowed in any MLB stadium in 2020 due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] (**): At the beginning of the season, there was a limit of 30% capacity due to COVID-19 restrictions implemented by Ohio Governor Mike DeWine.
[src:cleveland-guardians/cleveland-guardians-p03] On June 2, DeWine lifted the restrictions, and the team immediately allowed full capacity at Progressive Field.
